I can't afford a psychiatrist. I have severe anxiety and depression and it was crippling me. I dropped out of college, could not hold a job. It took me years to even talk to my PCP about it.
One day I did. And my life changed.
She prescribed me a SSRI and a therapist who was a social worker( so therapy was free.)
7 months later I'm a different person. I have hope for a better future. I'm so much healthier.
My PCP visit saved my life.
It's easy for a millionaire and a billionaire to prefer a visit to a psychiatrist. Poverty is not a concern for their mental health. For the rest of us, a PCP may be all that we have.

snippet.textDisplay: First time watching one of your videos but want to say a big THANK YOU. My personal story with Primary Care physicians and psychiatrists... I have severe agoraphobia (homebound for 5 years). I never sought help because I don't have health insurance & I was under the belief that I could only get help from a psychiatrist. I had an eye infection one day and went to my family's Primary Care...while seeing the doctor I burst into tears while asking him if I could ask him about my anxiety. He said yes and I was shocked! I talked to him about my current issues and my diagnoses from my younger years. He prescribed me medication and I went back to him every month then it became every 4 months once I got on a good combination of medication that worked well for me. During this period, he wondered if I was Bipolar and told me I needed to make an appt with a psychiatrist and that he would do all my lab work at the Primary Care because it would cost less (again no insurance). Unfortunately, the psychiatrist I saw was insanely expensive and I felt unheard by her. (just the personal MD not saying all are like this). Although I got my confirmation of being bipolar and went back to my Primary Care for medication management. It's less expensive and they are able to spread out my appts to help with the cost. My PC MD also recommended going back to therapy because medication alone can't help...the two really go together (for me and my mental health disorders, not speaking for anyone else!). I am so grateful for my Primary Care physicians for educating me and helping me get my life back on track and helping me in a safe way while also going around the "system" of high costs in health care. They are very cautious about what to prescribe. I hope no one misreads into those words Lady Gaga spoke and that anyone else in a situation like mine does not feel discouraged to seek help. Btw subscribed! Thanks again for this video!

snippet.textDisplay: This is a thoughtful post, and a nice description of an actual issue, i.e. the extent of the burden of illness that things like anxiety, depression, bipolar disorder and substance use problems represent -- versus the lack of available medical specialists in the U.S., both in terms of geography and in terms of affordability.  However, even most psychiatrists cannot, unfortunately, reliably distinguish between major depression and bipolar depression.  And even when they can sort out the diagnostic piece of things...many do not know how to treat bipolar disorder well.  So where does this leave primary care doctors...not to mention physician assistance and nurse practitioners?  All I can say is this:  if you working with a healthcare professional -- of any kind -- and you're not getting better with the treatments they are prescribing, then move on.  Find another doctor, if you can.  If that isn't possible, then work with what you've got...and suggest to your treating clinician, that she or he reconsider your diagnosis & your treatment plan.

That being said, I am a therapist and I'm also on anti-depressant, so I'm going to be talking both as a profesional and a patiant. My antidepressant is prescribed by my primary care doctor BUT I'm also seeing a therapist to help work on my depression. Usually in France, a consult with a primary care doctor is not long enough to actually work on the issues of the depressed patients. And, without therapy, why prescribe antidepressant? Just so that the person doesn"t drown in her depression? That's great, and of course if it's a moderate to intense depression phase, it has to be done. However, in the majority of patients, medication alone isn't enough to overcome depression or prevent a relapse in the long term.
Depression is a bit like if you were drowning in the ocean in too for from the shore. Antidepressants are a lifevest, but it is with therapy that you are going to be able to learn how to swimm back to safety.

I know that the healthcare system in broken in a lot of countries, and that psychiatrists are overwhelmed... However, this also explains why so many people take antidepressant for years, when, with the proper support and professional help, they could get better and actually go off medication.

This is a tricky one for me to comment on, because as I live in France, I'm not sure how it works in the US. 

That being said, I am a therapist and I'm also on anti-depressant, so I'm going to be talking both as a profesional and a patiant. My antidepressant is prescribed by my primary care doctor BUT I'm also seeing a therapist to help work on my depression. Usually in France, a consult with a primary care doctor is not long enough to actually work on the issues of the depressed patients. And, without therapy, why prescribe antidepressant? Just so that the person doesn"t drown in her depression? That's great, and of course if it's a moderate to intense depression phase, it has to be done. However, in the majority of patients, medication alone isn't enough to overcome depression or prevent a relapse in the long term. 
Depression is a bit like if you were drowning in the ocean in too for from the shore. Antidepressants are a lifevest, but it is with therapy that you are going to be able to learn how to swimm back to safety. 

I know that the healthcare system in broken in a lot of countries, and that psychiatrists are overwhelmed... However, this also explains why so many people take antidepressant for years, when, with the proper support and professional help, they could get better and actually go off medication. 

This is just my own personnal opinion, I hope I won't be offending anyone :)

As someone who has a chronic physical illness myself and have been practicing in the mental health field for just about a decade now I see nothing wrong with her statement.

They have general, primary care doctors... and specialists. My physical condition is rare enough that 95% of the time I tell the general doctors what I need, and then if they need to they follow up with my specialist.

Now, if it is prescription refill or you already have an accurate diagnosis with no new symptoms sure, a general doc will do just fine.

However expecting EVERY general doc to approach the situation like you seems a bit naive, and truthfully some of them may not have enough experience (or have a poor rapport with the patient and get wrong information) to make an accurate diagnosis.

People need a concrete, factual diagnosis when it comes to mental health. Not one that changes with each new doctor they see.
